		<link>https://ventureburn.com/what-is-solana-crypto/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Staff Reporter]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Sun, 14 Jun 2026 22:00:06 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[Cryptocurrency]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=200515</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Solana is one of the most recognizable crypto coins in the market today. It is one of the most talked-about networks because it solves the problem of how a blockchain</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/what-is-solana-crypto/" data-wpel-link="internal">What is Solana Crypto? A Beginner’s Guide to the SOL Blockchain</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana is one of the most recognizable crypto coins in the market today. It is one of the most talked-about networks because it solves the problem of how a blockchain can stay fast without making transactions expensive. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">It now ranks among the top 10 cryptocurrencies by market capitalization and is popular for being the “Ethereum killer.” More than its network, Solana has a thriving ecosystem of decentralized apps, NFTs, payments, gaming, and DeFi. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">However, while many people can recognize its name, if you ask what is Solana crypto, exactly? only a handful can explain. We will simplify all the information about Solana you will need to know in this guide.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">What is Solana Crypto? (Definition, Origin &amp; Overview)</span></h2>
<p><img decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-200519 aligncenter" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Solana-Logo.jpg" alt="" width="888" height="478" /></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">When people ask what is Solana crypto, they may be referring to the blockchain and the SOL cryptocurrency. This is a high speed, open-source platform for running decentralized applications (dApps) and processing transactions at lightning-fast speeds. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Solana blockchain was launched in 2020 by Anatoly Yakovenko, previously an engineer at Qualcomm, and it is fast. Solana is not Bitcoin, which is more of a store of value; hence, it is called the digital gold.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana uses various technologies to make sure it’s scalable. Now, Solana coin (SOL) is one of the biggest cryptocurrencies in market cap and is being used to create everything from global payments to complex NFT and digital art pieces.</span></p>
<h2><strong>How Does Solana Crypto Work? (The Tech Behind the Speed)</strong></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">To understand how does solana work, it helps to think of it as a blockchain that organizes information in a very efficient way before validators process it. Solana uses a combination of <a href="https://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/proof-stake-pos.asp" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external">Proof of Stake</a> and Proof of History to make transaction ordering faster and easier.</span></p>
<h3>Proof of History (PoH) in Solana Crypto Explained</h3>
<div id="attachment_200517" style="width: 766px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200517" class="wp-image-200517 size-full" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Proof-of-History.jpg" alt="How Does Solana Crypto Work? (The Tech Behind the Speed)" width="756" height="704" /><p id="caption-attachment-200517" class="wp-caption-text">Proof of History. Image Credit: CDN</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Proof of History (PoH) is not a separate coin or a marketing slogan. It is a core part of the way Solana orders time on-chain. PoH is the CNS of the Solana blockchain. On other blockchains like PoW or PoS, nodes need to agree before a transaction is approved. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The PoH uses a timestamp. It establishes that a certain event occurred at a certain time. Since all the validators agree on the timestamp, they don’t need to communicate with each other to validate the timestamp. This makes SOL crypto transactions much faster than other cryptos.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana Transaction Speed (TPS), Validators &amp; Low Fees</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The speed of a crypto network is described using TPS, which means transactions per second. The higher the TPS, the faster the network. Solana is one of the fastest there is. In theory, Solana would be able to process 65,000 transactions. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In 2025, it even crossed 107,000 TPS. But in practice, this is variable and will be affected by network congestion, app usage and the performance of the validators. Solana TPS can range from 1,500 to 4,000 TPS. This is not the absolute best but it’s still miles ahead of Bitcoin (3-7 TPS) and Ethereum (15-30 TPS).</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This high throughput is why fees on the network are typically less than $0.01, making it the go-to choice for retail users.</span></p>
<h2>What is the Solana Crypto Ecosystem Used For? (Use Cases)</h2>
<div id="attachment_200518" style="width: 1420px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200518" class="wp-image-200518 size-full" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Solana-Ecosystem.jpg" alt="What is the Solana Crypto Ecosystem Used For? (Use Cases)" width="1410" height="747" /><p id="caption-attachment-200518" class="wp-caption-text">Solana Ecosystem. Image: Bitunix</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">When we look at what is solana used for? The answer is almost everything. The Solana ecosystem has thousands of apps that make it almost like apps on an app store. The major uses you’ll find are:</span></p>
<h3>DeFi &amp; Earning Yield in the Solana Crypto Ecosystem</h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">A big solana use case is decentralized finance. On Solana, DeFi applications allow people to exchange tokens, lend assets, borrow money, and yield farm all without a bank.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This is where low fees are important because DeFi often comprises many small actions. On a more expensive blockchain, these actions can be prohibitively expensive. On Solana, the lower fees make it more user-friendly.</span></p>
<h3>NFTs and Web3 Gaming on Solana</h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Non-fungible tokens or NFTs helped put Solana on the map early on, and they continue to be important. Artists and collectors enjoy the reduced costs because they can create and exchange assets for lower fees.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Web3 gaming is also popular. Games require fast, responsive and consistent costs, and Solana is appealing to game developers for those reasons. DAOs and other community projects also benefit because the lower the cost of transactions, the easier it is for users to participate.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Meme Coins &amp; Global Payments</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Meme coins are an unusual but growing feature of the cryptocurrency market, and Solana is home to many of them. The speed and low cost of transactions help traders get out of meme coins quickly on Solana.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The low cost of transactions is also good for cross-border payments. In places with expensive remittance, Solana can be used to provide cheaper settlement for crypto-only transactions.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">What is SOL Crypto? (The Native Coin)</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The solana coin, or SOL, is the network’s backbone. It’s used for two purposes:</span></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Fees:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Every time you send money and use an app, you lose a little of SOL.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Staking:</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> Stake your SOL to assist in keeping the network secure and in the process, get </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/best-crypto-staking-platforms/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400;">staking</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> rewards.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">There is also a large number of Solana apps that would make you pay with SOL to do other things on the network. The token is, then, a significant element. SOL is the key to the Solana blockchain.</span></p>
<h2>Comparing Solana Crypto and Ethereum: Key Differences</h2>
<div id="attachment_200520" style="width: 1930px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200520" class="wp-image-200520 size-full" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/05/Solana-vs-Ethereum.jpg" alt="" width="1920" height="1080" /><p id="caption-attachment-200520" class="wp-caption-text">Solana vs Ethereum. Image Credit: Magic Eden</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana is frequently compared to Ethereum because they can be used to run smart contracts and dApps. Ethereum is more developed and more mature, whereas Solana is faster and less costly. It does everything Ethereum does, but much faster and cheaper. Hence, the name “Ethereum Killer”</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">However, Ethereum is more decentralized and has a longer history. A comparison of their features is indicated in the table below.</span></p>
<table>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><b>Feature</b></td>
<td><b>Solana</b></td>
<td><b>Ethereum</b></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">TPS</span></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">65,000+</span></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">~15-30</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Fees per transaction</span></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">$0.01</span></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">$0.5-$6</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Consensus</span></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">PoH + PoS</span></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">PoS</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">NFT Costs</span></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Very low</span></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Higher</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Developer Ecosystem</span></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Growing rapidly</span></td>
<td><span style="font-weight: 400;">Mature</span></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h2>Does Solana Crypto Have a Future? (Pros and Cons)</h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The future of Solana depends on execution, adoption, and network reliability. The project has clear strengths and some weaknesses. Below are the pros and cons of Solana.</span></p>
<p><b>Pros of Solana</b></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana’s blazing speed makes it very appealing for mainstream blockchain use.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Near-zero fees enable cost-effective access to DeFi, NFTs and payments.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Growing Solana ecosystem attracts developers, startups and leading Web3 projects, fueling bullish </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/solana-price-prediction/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana price prediction</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;">s.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Passive income opportunities and security through SOL staking.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana’s scalable infrastructure positions it well for mainstream financial and gaming applications.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Strong institutional and retail interest boosts long-term visibility and adoption potential.</span></li>
</ul>
<p><b>Cons of Solana</b></p>
<ul>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Historical outages could decrease confidence in network stability and reliability.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">High validator requirements make the network more centralized than its competitors.</span></li>
<li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Price volatility in SOL may pose a major risk for new investors.</span></li>
</ul>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">Conclusion: The Bottom Line on the Solana Blockchain</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana is an application-focused, high-performance, low-cost blockchain network. The SOL crypto is the coin that powers the blockchain and its entire ecosystem. Its unique Proof of History consensus model makes it able to achieve very high efficiency and scalability. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">This speed has made Solana the perfect ecosystem for developers. Its focus on speed is particularly well-suited to DeFi, NFTs, gaming and payments. The rapidly growing ecosystem and the increasing interest from institutional investors make Solana one of the most exciting cryptos to watch in 2026 and beyond.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400;">FAQs About Solana Coin</span></h2>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">What is Solana crypto?</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana crypto is a fast and cheap blockchain, with SOL as its token.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">How does Solana work?</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana uses a combination of Proof of Stake and Proof of History to efficiently order and validate transactions.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">What can you do with Solana?</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana is used for decentralized finance (DeFi), NFTs, gaming, payments, and more.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Is Solana a good investment?</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Solana is considered a good investment. But due to the unpredictability of the cryptocurrency market, it can be volatile.  </span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">What is Solana transaction speed?</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In perfect conditions, the Solana speed is 65,000 TPS. Due to different conditions, it is usually 1,500-4,000 TPS.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Is Solana blockchain secure?</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Yes. Though it has suffered from uptime problems in the past, where the network has gone offline, funds stored on the network have not been compromised. The 2026 “Alpenglow” upgrade is designed to stop these pauses from happening.</span></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Can I mine Solana?</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">No, Solana is not minable like Bitcoin. You will need to “stake” your coins to receive rewards and help the network.</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/what-is-solana-crypto/" data-wpel-link="internal">What is Solana Crypto? A Beginner’s Guide to the SOL Blockchain</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
